@{B}Introduction@{UB}
~~~~~~~~~~~~
   This is a CLI/Shell only Utility and isn't really for the beginner, but
then again, any one who has to suffer the company of PC's, really.  This is
mainly aimed at PC users.  :-(

   If you use a PC at work, running MSDOS and come home to a wonderful
@{I}Amiga@{UI} running AmigaDOS, you will appreciate the differences between the
two operating systems.

@{B}So how does it work?@{UB}

   When you Install "MSDOSŪ For AmigaDOSŪ", you create a directory in which
to place your MS-DOS commands, this can be anywhere you like, preferably on
your boot disk.

   "MSDOSŪ For AmigaDOSŪ" is for Shell use only certainly not Workbench, nor
is it a commodity.  It is a collection of AmigaDOSŪ Aliases which are made
resident upon startup.  These aliases work by creating temporary substitutes
for AmigaDOS commands.  So when you type DEL at the Shell, it really runs
the AmigaDOS delete instruction.  Like this, this package will save you loads
of time when working in a Shell.  Some commands cannot work as ALIAS'es so
they are script (batch) files instead.  The script files allow interactive
usage of MS-DOS commands such as DELTREE which is a command AmigaDOSŪ lacks
that allows you to delete an entire directory tree (The AmigaDOSŪ equivalent
is Delete <name> all quiet).

@{B}What is MSDOS for AmigaDOS?@{UB}

   Quite simply- it allows you to use MSDOS commands on your AMIGA, most
of which are conveniently shorter and there are a few extra commands.

Here's some features:

   · Enables the use of commands like Del, Deltree, Pause, DOSKey, etc.
   · No need to alter existing Workbench commands
   · Works with RESIDENT commands too!   (One or two, like DELTREE don't)
   · Takes up VERY LITTLE RAM!
   · Fully AmigaDOS 2+ compatible, & works on ANY device (irrelevent!).
   · Completely invisible-  AmigaDOS commands still work as well!
   · Doesn't echo commands.  It's "QUIET" like MSDOS
   · Can use * wildcard!
   · Also allows you to use . as current directory and .. as parent
   · Double click an MS-DOS icon, and get an MS-DOS supporting DosShell
   · Use A: and B:, instead of boring old DF0: and DF1:

   If you are a regular user of both @{I}MS-DOS@{UI} and @{I}AmigaDOS@{UI}, then this is for
you.  MSDOS for AmigaDOS DOES NOT erase any current AmigaDOS commands, it
simply ADDS MS-DOS ones to the system using very cunning ALIASES and BATCH
files.  This means that, for example you could use DEL or DELETE if you wanted
to delete a file.

   Here's a quick example of how @{I}MS-DOS@{UI} --CAN-- be shorter than AmigaDOS:

@{U}Operation@{UU}                   @{U}AmigaDOS@{UU}                   @{U}MS-DOS Equiv'@{UU}

Delete all files            Delete #?                  Del.
Delete *.info files         Delete #?.info             Del *.info
Delete a directory          Delete <name> all          DelTree <name>
                            Delete <name>.info
CD to These_Are_The_Docs    CD These_Are_The_Docs      QCD These
Format a disk               Format drive df0: name     Format A:
                            Empty noicons

You CAN also do "Del." because I made a seperate command to do this.
NB:  Although . and .. will work for Current directory and Parent
directories respectively, if you have installed DosWedge, you CANNOT do
"Del ."  <<  There must be NO SPACE between "Del" and "."  DOS doesn't
allow you to literally remove the entire Current Directory!  I think you
might get an `object in use' error, IF it doesn't get baffled first at
what you're trying to do! :-)  Use "Del." which removes the @{i}contents@{ui} of
the directory!

More details on these DOS patches later!

Like @{I}MS-DOS@{UI}, All commands I have implemented are "quiet".  This means that
they do not say anything in response unless there was an error.

   For example:

   @{U}AmigaDOS@{UU}                      @{U}MS-DOS@{UU}

   H:> Delete Test.Txt           H:> Del Test.Txt
       Test.Txt Deleted          H:>
   H:>

Notice how MS-DOS tells you nothing, as usual.  Well now, your Amiga can
be quiet too, without bothering to add that annoying "quiet" parameter on
the end!
@EndNode

@Node MSDOS_INSTALLATION
@Next MSDOS_COMMANDS
